This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.
result.caption: State of Wisconsin vs. Vincent Frank Hill

records.descr: Pet for appointment counsel,affidavit of indigency

records.addlTxt: No violent or abusive contact with BJP. No use or possession of alcohol.

3:37 PM Defendant Vincent Frank Hill in court.  Attorney Chad LaLor in court for State of Wisconsin. Court calls case. Defendant receives complaint. Court recites charges against defendant and possible penalties. Defendant pleads not guilty to count 1. Guilty on count 2. Court accepts pleas. Court enters not guilty pleas on defendant's behalf on count 2 and will address count 2 at next hearing. Defendant waives reading of complaint. Defendant advised of right to consult an attorney. 
State requests bond posted of $500 to continue, no violent or abusive contact with BJP, no alcohol. Cites priors. 
Defendant has no objection.
Court orders $500 cash, no violent or abusive contact with BJP, no use or possession of alcohol. 
Defendant will retain attorney. Court advises defendant of right to waive attorney paperwork for DA.
Status conference scheduled for November 11, 2022 at 09:00 am.
Bail receipt, no court date listed
